Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lua->HIR Translator - Complete translation from Lua AST to HIR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Translates Lua constructs to High-level Intermediate Representation
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/lua/lua_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/lua/lua_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Carries the bridge state between the Lua AST and the emerging HIR module so
every translate_* helper can accumulate diagnostics without re-walking the
source. ast_root is the entry node from lua_parser; hir_module is the HIR
root that translate_program populates. errors is an append-only list mutated
by translation_error; had_error is set to 1 on the first error to short-
circuit downstream consumers that test it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
The context is an idiomatic value-of-type struct: construction allocates the
heap home directly and the binding is the struct pointer. Helpers re-bind the
pointer with a typed Let so field reads/writes are managed by the type system
and mutations write in place - no read/write round-trips are required.
@End Implementation
Type called "LuaToHIRContext":
    ast_root as Integer            Note: Lua AST root node
    hir_module as Integer          Note: HIR module being constructed
    errors as Integer              Note: List of translation error strings
    had_error as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Context Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds a fresh translation context bound to the supplied AST root and a new
HIR module named "lua_module" - downstream renaming can override this once the
actual Lua file path is known. The errors list starts empty and had_error at 0.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Constructs the HIR module via hir_create_module and names it via
hir_set_module_name. Struct construction allocates the context's heap home
directly; the binding returned is the pointer the caller receives.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_translation_context" takes ast_root as Integer returns Integer:
    Let module_node be proc hir_create_module from HIR
    proc hir_set_module_name from HIR with module_node, "lua_module"

    Let ctx be a value of type LuaToHIRContext with
        ast_root as ast_root,
        hir_module as module_node,
        errors as proc list_create from ListCore,
        had_error as 0

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Translation errors are accumulated in the context's error list so the full
batch can be reported instead of aborting on the first failure; this gives
better diagnostics for source files with multiple issues. The had_error flag
is the cheap "any errors at all?" query used by had_translation_errors.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Re-bind the context pointer with a typed Let; append the message to the error
list and set had_error to 1 in place.
@End Implementation
Process called "translation_error" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    Let ctx as LuaToHIRContext be ctx_ptr
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.errors, message
    Set ctx.had_error to 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The expression dispatcher routes to a leaf-specific translator based on the
LuaASTNode.node_type tag. Tag ordering puts literals first, then identifier,
then composite forms (binary/unary/call/table/function/vararg) and finally
indexing/field access; this matches expected frequency in real Lua code so
the common cases hit early branches. Unknown tags fall through to
translation_error returning 0 so the caller can detect failure without
crashing the entire translation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be expr_node

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_NIL_LITERAL:
        Return proc translate_nil_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_BOOLEAN_LITERAL:
        Return proc translate_boolean_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_NUMBER_LITERAL:
        Return proc translate_number_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return proc translate_string_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc translate_identifier with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_BINARY_OP:
        Return proc translate_binary_op with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_UNARY_OP:
        Return proc translate_unary_op with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION_CALL:
        Return proc translate_function_call with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_CONSTRUCTOR:
        Return proc translate_table_constructor with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION_EXPRESSION:
        Return proc translate_function_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_VARARG:
        Return proc translate_vararg with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_INDEX_ACCESS:
        Return proc translate_index_access with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FIELD_ACCESS:
        Return proc translate_field_access with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    proc translation_error with ctx_ptr, "Unknown expression type"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua 'nil' maps to HIR's null literal, which is semantically equivalent to an
empty Optional. Producing a proper typed null literal (rather than a raw
integer constant) preserves Lua's semantics that nil is its OWN type, not a
sentinel value of another type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_nil_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_create_null_literal from HIR
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Lua AST stores boolean literals as the string "true" or "false"; we map
that to the HIR boolean literal's 0/1 payload. The HIR boolean literal carries
the truth value directly so downstream consumers need not re-parse a string.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_boolean_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node

    Let value be 0
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "true" is equal to 1:
        Set value to 1
    End If

    Return proc hir_create_bool_literal from HIR with value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua numbers are distinguished into integer and float subtypes (Lua 5.3+). We
classify the lexeme: a literal containing '.', an exponent marker ('e'/'E'),
or a hex-float marker ('p'/'P') is a float; everything else (including plain
integers and hex integers) is an integer. Integers lower to a HIR integer
literal and floats to a HIR float literal so downstream type analysis sees the
correct numeric subtype without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_number_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node
    Let lexeme be ast_node.value

    Let is_float be 0
    If proc string_contains from StringUtils with lexeme, "." is equal to 1:
        Set is_float to 1
    End If
    If proc string_contains from StringUtils with lexeme, "e" is equal to 1:
        Set is_float to 1
    End If
    If proc string_contains from StringUtils with lexeme, "E" is equal to 1:
        Set is_float to 1
    End If

    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Let fval be proc string_to_float from StringUtils with lexeme
        Return proc hir_create_float_literal from HIR with fval
    End If

    Let ival be proc string_to_integer from StringUtils with lexeme
    Return proc hir_create_int_literal from HIR with ival
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua string literals are already escape-decoded by the upstream lexer/parser
(both '...' and "..." forms plus the [[...]] long form), so we receive the
literal value as a clean string. No further quoting work happens here - the
HIR literal stores the raw character data and re-quoting for any target
language is the responsibility of the respective backend.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_string_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node
    Return proc hir_create_string_literal from HIR with ast_node.value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifiers in Lua resolve at runtime against the active environment table
(_ENV), but at HIR translation time we only need to record the textual name -
binding resolution happens during the semantic phase that follows translation.
The identifier value field carries the source name verbatim.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_identifier" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node
    Return proc hir_create_identifier from HIR with ast_node.value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's binary operators include arithmetic, comparison, logical, string
concatenation (..), floor-division (//) and the bitwise operators added in
5.3+. We translate the children before constructing the binary node so the
operand HIR nodes exist when the binary HIR node is built. Lua-specific
operators with no direct HIR opcode (concat '..', power '^') are mapped to the
closest HIR opcode and tagged with metadata so backends can re-emit the exact
Lua form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_op" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node

    Let left_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let right_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1

    Let left_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, left_ast
    Let right_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, right_ast

    Let hir_operator be proc map_lua_operator_to_hir with ast_node.value

    Let hir_binary be proc hir_create_binary_expr from HIR with hir_operator, left_hir, right_hir

    Note: Lua concatenation and power have no native HIR opcode; tag the source form
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, ".." is equal to 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_binary, "lua_operator", "concat"
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "^" is equal to 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_binary, "lua_operator", "power"
    End If

    Return hir_binary
End Process

@Reasoning:
The operator string -> HIR opcode mapping is an unrolled sequence of
string_equals checks because Lua has roughly 20 binary operators and a hash-
table lookup would require an extra allocation. Lua's '..' (concat) maps to
HIR_OP_ADD as a structural placeholder disambiguated by the "lua_operator"
metadata; '^' (power) maps to HIR_OP_MULTIPLY similarly; '//' (floor division)
maps to HIR_OP_INT_DIVIDE which is its exact HIR equivalent. The branch order
roughly matches expected frequency for branch-predictor friendliness.
@End Reasoning
Process called "map_lua_operator_to_hir" takes operator as String returns Integer:
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "+" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_ADD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "-" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_SUBTRACT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "*" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "/" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_DIVIDE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "//" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_INT_DIVIDE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "%" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_MODULO
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "^" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, ".." is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_ADD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "==" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_EQUAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "~=" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_NOT_EQUAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "<" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_THAN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, ">" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_THAN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "<=" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, ">=" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_EQUAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "and" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_AND
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "or" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_OR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "&" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_AND
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "|" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_OR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "~" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_XOR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, "<<" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_LEFT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with operator, ">>" is equal to 1:
        Return HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_RIGHT
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Unknown operator
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's four unary operators are -, not, # (length), and ~ (bitwise not). The
length operator # is Lua-specific - it returns a border count for tables and
code-unit length for strings and is overloadable via __len. HIR has no native
length opcode, so we lower # to HIR_OP_NEGATE as a structural placeholder and
tag the node with "lua_operator"="length" metadata so backends re-emit '#'.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_unary_op" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node

    Let operand_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let operand_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, operand_ast

    Let hir_operator be HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE
    Let is_length be 0

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "-" is equal to 1:
        Set hir_operator to HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "not" is equal to 1:
        Set hir_operator to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "#" is equal to 1:
        Set hir_operator to HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE
        Set is_length to 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with ast_node.value, "~" is equal to 1:
        Set hir_operator to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_NOT
    End If

    Let hir_unary be proc hir_create_unary_expr from HIR with hir_operator, operand_hir

    If is_length is equal to 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_unary, "lua_operator", "length"
    End If

    Return hir_unary
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua call expressions cover both regular calls f(x,y) and method calls
obj:m(x,y) (sugar for obj.m(obj,x,y)). The method distinction is detected by
inspecting whether the callee's node type is LUA_FIELD_ACCESS, and if so we
tag the HIR call with "lua_method_call" metadata so the backend can thread the
receiver as the implicit first argument. Function resolution is deferred to
semantic analysis because Lua's runtime dispatch via metatables cannot be
resolved at translation time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let callee_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let callee_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, callee_ast

    Let args_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let arg_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with args_ast

    Let hir_call be proc hir_create_call_expr from HIR with callee_hir

    Let arg_index be 0
    While arg_index is less than arg_count:
        Let arg_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with args_ast, arg_index
        Let arg_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_ast
        proc hir_add_argument from HIR with hir_call, arg_hir
        Set arg_index to arg_index plus 1
    End While

    Let callee_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be callee_ast
    If callee_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FIELD_ACCESS:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_call, "lua_method_call", "true"
    End If

    Return hir_call
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua tables are a single runtime type but two semantic shapes: list-like
(consecutive integer keys from 1) and dictionary-like (named or explicit-key
fields). We scan all fields once: any named or [expr]-indexed field forces a
map literal, while a pure run of unkeyed positional values produces a list
literal. This biases toward the more efficient representation while remaining
correct for the mixed case.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_table_constructor" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let field_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let has_keyed_fields be 0

    Let field_index be 0
    While field_index is less than field_count:
        Let field_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, field_index
        Let field_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be field_ast

        If field_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED:
            Set has_keyed_fields to 1
        End If
        If field_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED:
            Set has_keyed_fields to 1
        End If

        Set field_index to field_index plus 1
    End While

    If has_keyed_fields is equal to 1:
        Return proc translate_table_as_dictionary with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    Return proc translate_table_as_array with ctx_ptr, node
End Process

@Reasoning:
When the table constructor is array-like (all fields unkeyed positional
values), we extract the value expression from each field and append it to the
HIR list literal in source order. Lua's 1-based indexing is NOT reflected in
the HIR list - HIR lists are 0-indexed and the 1-based access is reintroduced
at codegen only when the target preserves Lua semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_table_as_array" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let field_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let hir_list be proc hir_create_list_literal from HIR

    Let field_index be 0
    While field_index is less than field_count:
        Let field_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, field_index
        Let value_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 0
        Let value_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_ast
        proc hir_add_list_element from HIR with hir_list, value_hir
        Set field_index to field_index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dictionary translation distinguishes three field kinds: named (name = value)
becomes a string-keyed entry; indexed ([key] = value) preserves the key
expression verbatim; positional fields embedded in an otherwise-dictionary
table get synthesized integer keys from their iteration index (1-based, per
Lua array semantics). Each (key, value) pair is appended as a map entry.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_table_as_dictionary" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let field_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let hir_map be proc hir_create_map_literal from HIR

    Let array_position be 1
    Let field_index be 0
    While field_index is less than field_count:
        Let field_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, field_index
        Let field_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be field_ast

        If field_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED:
            Let name_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 0
            Let name_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be name_ast
            Let key_hir be proc hir_create_string_literal from HIR with name_node.value

            Let value_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 1
            Let value_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_ast

            proc hir_add_map_entry from HIR with hir_map, key_hir, value_hir
        End If

        If field_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED:
            Let ikey_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 0
            Let ikey_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, ikey_ast

            Let ivalue_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 1
            Let ivalue_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, ivalue_ast

            proc hir_add_map_entry from HIR with hir_map, ikey_hir, ivalue_hir
        End If

        If field_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD:
            Let pkey_hir be proc hir_create_int_literal from HIR with array_position
            Set array_position to array_position plus 1

            Let pvalue_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field_ast, 0
            Let pvalue_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, pvalue_ast

            proc hir_add_map_entry from HIR with hir_map, pkey_hir, pvalue_hir
        End If

        Set field_index to field_index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_map
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function expressions ('function(args) body end' as a value) translate to HIR
lambdas. Lua's varargs '...' parameter is handled by adding a parameter whose
name is literally "..." - the HIR backend recognises that name as a vararg
slot. The body is translated as a block so nested statement-level constructs
are preserved, and attached via hir_set_lambda_block_body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir_lambda be proc hir_create_lambda from HIR

    Let params_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let param_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with params_ast

    Let param_index be 0
    While param_index is less than param_count:
        Let param_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with params_ast, param_index
        Let param_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be param_ast

        Let hir_param be proc hir_create_parameter from HIR
        If param_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_VARARG:
            proc hir_set_parameter_name from HIR with hir_param, "..."
        Otherwise:
            proc hir_set_parameter_name from HIR with hir_param, param_node.value
        End If
        proc hir_add_parameter from HIR with hir_lambda, hir_param

        Set param_index to param_index plus 1
    End While

    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast
    proc hir_set_lambda_block_body from HIR with hir_lambda, body_hir

    Return hir_lambda
End Process

@Reasoning:
The vararg expression '...' is treated as a special identifier in HIR rather
than a new node type because HIR's identifier resolution scheme can be
extended via the metadata system. We tag the identifier with "lua_vararg" so
backends can lower it to their target language's vararg form without a name-
string comparison.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_vararg" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir_node be proc hir_create_identifier from HIR with "..."
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_node, "lua_vararg", "true"
    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bracket-form index access 'tbl[expr]' is the general indexing form in Lua; the
key can be ANY Lua value. We translate both children recursively and create a
HIR index expression. The element type is resolved later by value-flow
analysis rather than syntactically.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_index_access" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let index_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1

    Let object_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_ast
    Let index_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, index_ast

    Return proc hir_create_index_expr from HIR with object_hir, index_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dot-form field access 'tbl.name' is sugar for 'tbl["name"]' with a static key,
but HIR represents it as a distinct member expression because that preserves
the field-name string for languages that distinguish struct field access from
dictionary indexing. Member resolution to a layout offset is a semantic-
analysis question deferred past translation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_field_access" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let field_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let field_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be field_ast

    Let object_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_ast

    Return proc hir_create_member_expr from HIR with object_hir, field_node.value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The statement dispatcher mirrors translate_expression for statement-position
constructs. Lua's grammar allows function calls in statement position with
their return values discarded, so LUA_FUNCTION_CALL nodes route through
translate_function_call wrapped as an expression statement. Anything that
does not match a known statement form falls through to translate_expression
because Lua's grammar allows expressions in statement position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, stmt_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be stmt_node

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IF_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_if_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_WHILE_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_while_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_REPEAT_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_repeat_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FOR_NUMERIC:
        Return proc translate_for_numeric with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FOR_GENERIC:
        Return proc translate_for_generic with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION:
        Return proc translate_function_declaration with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_LOCAL_DECLARATION:
        Return proc translate_local_declaration with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_ASSIGNMENT:
        Return proc translate_assignment with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_RETURN_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_return_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_BREAK_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_break_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_LABEL_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_label_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_GOTO_STATEMENT:
        Return proc translate_goto_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION_CALL:
        Let call_hir be proc translate_function_call with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
        Return proc hir_create_expression_statement from HIR with call_hir
    End If

    Let expr_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    Return proc hir_create_expression_statement from HIR with expr_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's parser flattens if-elseif-else chains into a single AST node whose
children are condition, then-block, then optionally further condition/block
pairs for each elseif, with a trailing standalone block being the else-clause
when present. We reconstruct a proper nested HIR if tree from this flat form
so HIR consumers see the same recursive shape as other source languages. Each
elseif becomes the else-branch of the previous if; the final lone block
becomes the innermost else-branch. We build the chain right-to-left so each
inner if is fully assembled before being attached as the previous level's
else branch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_if_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let child_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Note: First pass - collect condition/block boundaries.
    Note: children: cond0, block0, [cond1, block1, ...], [else_block]
    Note: Determine whether a trailing else block exists: odd remaining count after pairs.
    Let pair_end be child_count
    Let has_else be 0
    Let else_index be 0

    Note: Count: a sequence of (cond, block) pairs, optionally one trailing block.
    Note: If child_count is odd, the last child is the else block.
    Let remainder be child_count
    Let half be 0
    While half plus half is less than remainder:
        Set half to half plus 1
    End While
    If half plus half is greater than remainder:
        Note: child_count was odd: last child is else block
        Set has_else to 1
        Set else_index to child_count minus 1
        Set pair_end to child_count minus 1
    End If

    Note: Build the innermost else branch first.
    Let else_hir be 0
    If has_else is equal to 1:
        Let else_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, else_index
        Set else_hir to proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, else_ast
    End If

    Note: Walk the condition/block pairs from last to first, nesting each as the
    Note: else branch of the one before it.
    Let pair_count be 0
    While pair_count plus pair_count is less than pair_end:
        Set pair_count to pair_count plus 1
    End While

    Let current_else be else_hir
    Let idx be pair_count minus 1
    While idx is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let cond_pos be idx plus idx
        Let block_pos be cond_pos plus 1

        Let cond_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, cond_pos
        Let cond_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, cond_ast

        Let block_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, block_pos
        Let block_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, block_ast

        Let hir_if be proc hir_create_if from HIR
        proc hir_set_if_condition from HIR with hir_if, cond_hir
        proc hir_set_if_then from HIR with hir_if, block_hir
        If current_else is not equal to 0:
            proc hir_set_if_else from HIR with hir_if, current_else
        End If

        Set current_else to hir_if
        Set idx to idx minus 1
    End While

    Return current_else
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua while-loops are the pre-test loop form: condition evaluated at loop top,
zero iterations possible. We build a HIR while node and attach the translated
condition and body. Loop scope and break-target binding are established later
by the semantic analyser.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_while_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let condition_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let condition_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_ast

    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast

    Let hir_while be proc hir_create_while from HIR
    proc hir_set_while_condition from HIR with hir_while, condition_hir
    proc hir_set_while_body from HIR with hir_while, body_hir

    Return hir_while
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's 'repeat ... until cond' has post-test semantics with INVERTED condition
polarity: the loop continues while cond is FALSE and exits when cond becomes
true. We translate by negating the condition with HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT and
emitting a HIR while node tagged with "lua_repeat_until" metadata so the
backend can pick the do-while lowering. The negation produces a HIR shape
identical to other languages' do-while loops, keeping the pipeline language-
agnostic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_repeat_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast

    Let condition_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let condition_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_ast

    Let negated_condition be proc hir_create_unary_expr from HIR with HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT, condition_hir

    Let hir_while be proc hir_create_while from HIR
    proc hir_set_while_condition from HIR with hir_while, negated_condition
    proc hir_set_while_body from HIR with hir_while, body_hir
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_while, "lua_repeat_until", "true"

    Return hir_while
End Process

@Reasoning:
The numeric-for is Lua's 'for i = start, end[, step] do ... end' form. Step
defaults to 1 when omitted. We lower it to a C-style HIR for statement: init
binds the loop variable to start (via a variable declaration), the condition
tests i <= end, the update increments i by step, and the body is the
translated block. The bounds and the loop variable name are preserved exactly
so backends can re-emit the numeric-for or any equivalent counted loop.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_for_numeric" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let child_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let var_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let var_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be var_ast

    Let start_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let start_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, start_ast

    Let end_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 2
    Let end_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, end_ast

    Let step_hir be 0
    Let body_index be 3

    If child_count is greater than 4:
        Let step_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 3
        Set step_hir to proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, step_ast
        Set body_index to 4
    Otherwise:
        Set step_hir to proc hir_create_int_literal from HIR with 1
    End If

    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, body_index
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast

    Note: Build init: var = start
    Let init_var be proc hir_create_variable from HIR
    proc hir_set_variable_name from HIR with init_var, var_node.value
    proc hir_set_variable_initializer from HIR with init_var, start_hir

    Note: Build condition: var <= end
    Let cond_left be proc hir_create_identifier from HIR with var_node.value
    Let cond_hir be proc hir_create_binary_expr from HIR with HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL, cond_left, end_hir

    Note: Build update: var = var + step
    Let upd_left be proc hir_create_identifier from HIR with var_node.value
    Let upd_add be proc hir_create_binary_expr from HIR with HIR.HIR_OP_ADD, upd_left, step_hir
    Let upd_target be proc hir_create_identifier from HIR with var_node.value
    Let upd_hir be proc hir_create_assign_expr from HIR with upd_target, HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_SIMPLE, upd_add

    Let hir_for be proc hir_create_for from HIR
    proc hir_set_for_init from HIR with hir_for, init_var
    proc hir_set_for_condition from HIR with hir_for, cond_hir
    proc hir_set_for_update from HIR with hir_for, upd_hir
    proc hir_set_for_body from HIR with hir_for, body_hir
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_for, "lua_numeric_for", "true"

    Return hir_for
End Process

@Reasoning:
The generic-for 'for v1[,v2,...] in expr1[,expr2,...] do ... end' calls expr1
with (state, control) on each iteration. We lower it to a HIR for-in statement
binding the primary control variable to the primary iterator expression, and
annotate the loop with "lua_multi_var"/"lua_multi_iterator" metadata when the
source had more than one of either so the backend can unpack the iterator's
multi-return tuple into the additional bindings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_for_generic" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let vars_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let var_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with vars_ast

    Let first_var_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with vars_ast, 0
    Let first_var_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be first_var_ast

    Let exprs_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let expr_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with exprs_ast

    Let iterator_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with exprs_ast, 0
    Let iterator_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, iterator_ast

    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 2
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast

    Let hir_for be proc hir_create_for_in from HIR
    proc hir_set_for_in_variable from HIR with hir_for, first_var_node.value
    proc hir_set_for_in_iterable from HIR with hir_for, iterator_hir
    proc hir_set_for_in_body from HIR with hir_for, body_hir

    If var_count is greater than 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_for, "lua_multi_var", "true"
    End If
    If expr_count is greater than 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_for, "lua_multi_iterator", "true"
    End If

    Return hir_for
End Process

@Reasoning:
'function name(...) body end' and 'function tbl.name(...) body end' both arrive
here. The dot/colon-prefixed form encodes its name as a LUA_FIELD_ACCESS
subtree where the leaf identifier is the method name and the receiver is the
table; we extract the method name for the HIR function's flat name string and
record the receiver table name in metadata. Plain declarations use the
identifier verbatim. Lua functions are public by default.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function_declaration" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let name_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be name_ast

    Let func_name be ""
    Let table_name be ""
    Let is_method be 0
    If name_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FIELD_ACCESS:
        Let field_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with name_ast, 1
        Let field_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be field_ast
        Set func_name to field_node.value
        Set is_method to 1

        Let table_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with name_ast, 0
        Let table_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be table_ast
        Set table_name to table_node.value
    Otherwise:
        Set func_name to name_node.value
    End If

    Let hir_function be proc hir_create_function from HIR
    proc hir_set_function_name from HIR with hir_function, func_name

    Let params_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let param_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with params_ast

    Let param_index be 0
    While param_index is less than param_count:
        Let param_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with params_ast, param_index
        Let param_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be param_ast

        Let hir_param be proc hir_create_parameter from HIR
        If param_node.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_VARARG:
            proc hir_set_parameter_name from HIR with hir_param, "..."
        Otherwise:
            proc hir_set_parameter_name from HIR with hir_param, param_node.value
        End If
        proc hir_add_parameter from HIR with hir_function, hir_param

        Set param_index to param_index plus 1
    End While

    Let body_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 2
    Let body_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, body_ast
    proc hir_set_function_body from HIR with hir_function, body_hir

    If is_method is equal to 1:
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_function, "lua_method_table", table_name
    End If

    Return hir_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua 'local' declarations bind one or more names with optional parallel
initialisers; missing initialisers default to nil, and excess initialisers are
discarded. We translate by walking the name list, materialising a HIR variable
for each name paired with the corresponding initialiser (or a synthetic nil
literal when absent). A single binding returns the bare variable; multiple
bindings are wrapped in a HIR block so the sequence is preserved as one
statement.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_local_declaration" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let child_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let names_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let name_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with names_ast

    Let init_exprs be 0
    Let init_count be 0
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Set init_exprs to proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
        Set init_count to proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with init_exprs
    End If

    Note: Build variables, tracking whether to wrap.
    Let first_var be 0
    Let wrapper_block be 0

    Let var_index be 0
    While var_index is less than name_count:
        Let var_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with names_ast, var_index
        Let var_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be var_ast

        Let init_hir be 0
        If var_index is less than init_count:
            Let init_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with init_exprs, var_index
            Set init_hir to proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, init_ast
        Otherwise:
            Set init_hir to proc hir_create_null_literal from HIR
        End If

        Let hir_var be proc hir_create_variable from HIR
        proc hir_set_variable_name from HIR with hir_var, var_node.value
        proc hir_set_variable_initializer from HIR with hir_var, init_hir
        proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_var, "lua_local", "true"

        If var_index is equal to 0:
            Set first_var to hir_var
        Otherwise:
            If wrapper_block is equal to 0:
                Set wrapper_block to proc hir_create_block from HIR
                proc hir_add_statement from HIR with wrapper_block, first_var
            End If
            proc hir_add_statement from HIR with wrapper_block, hir_var
        End If

        Set var_index to var_index plus 1
    End While

    If wrapper_block is not equal to 0:
        Return wrapper_block
    End If
    Return first_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiple assignment 'a, b = x, y' is positional: lhs[i] gets rhs[i]; any
unfilled lhs entries get nil. We emit one HIR assignment expression per lhs
target wrapped as an expression statement rather than a single multi-assign
node, because the HIR consumers treat each target's resolution independently.
A single target returns the lone assignment statement; multiple targets are
wrapped in a HIR block.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_assignment" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lhs_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let lhs_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with lhs_ast

    Let rhs_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let rhs_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with rhs_ast

    Let first_stmt be 0
    Let wrapper_block be 0

    Let assign_index be 0
    While assign_index is less than lhs_count:
        Let target_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with lhs_ast, assign_index
        Let target_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, target_ast

        Let value_hir be 0
        If assign_index is less than rhs_count:
            Let value_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with rhs_ast, assign_index
            Set value_hir to proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_ast
        Otherwise:
            Set value_hir to proc hir_create_null_literal from HIR
        End If

        Let assign_expr be proc hir_create_assign_expr from HIR with target_hir, HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_SIMPLE, value_hir
        Let assign_stmt be proc hir_create_expression_statement from HIR with assign_expr

        If assign_index is equal to 0:
            Set first_stmt to assign_stmt
        Otherwise:
            If wrapper_block is equal to 0:
                Set wrapper_block to proc hir_create_block from HIR
                proc hir_add_statement from HIR with wrapper_block, first_stmt
            End If
            proc hir_add_statement from HIR with wrapper_block, assign_stmt
        End If

        Set assign_index to assign_index plus 1
    End While

    If wrapper_block is not equal to 0:
        Return wrapper_block
    End If
    Return first_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua returns can carry zero values (bare 'return'), one value, or multiple
values. An empty return becomes a return with no value; a single-value return
attaches that value; a multi-value return packs the values into a HIR list
literal as the return value and tags the node "lua_multi_return" so backends
that lack multiple-return-values can unwrap appropriately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_return_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let child_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node

    Let hir_return be proc hir_create_return from HIR

    If child_count is equal to 0:
        Return hir_return
    End If

    Let exprs_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let expr_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with exprs_ast

    If expr_count is equal to 1:
        Let value_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with exprs_ast, 0
        Let value_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_ast
        proc hir_set_return_value from HIR with hir_return, value_hir
        Return hir_return
    End If

    Note: Multiple return values - pack into a list literal.
    Let values_list be proc hir_create_list_literal from HIR
    Let value_index be 0
    While value_index is less than expr_count:
        Let mv_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with exprs_ast, value_index
        Let mv_hir be proc translate_expression with ctx_ptr, mv_ast
        proc hir_add_list_element from HIR with values_list, mv_hir
        Set value_index to value_index plus 1
    End While

    proc hir_set_return_value from HIR with hir_return, values_list
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_return, "lua_multi_return", "true"

    Return hir_return
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua break has no label form and always exits the innermost enclosing loop; the
HIR break statement carries no target because loop-exit binding is established
during semantic analysis. The translator produces a bare break node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_break_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_create_break from HIR
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua 5.2+ labels '::name::' are rare but legal; HIR has no native label so we
represent them as a continue node (the nearest no-payload control node) tagged
with "lua_label" metadata holding the name. The semantic analyser threads the
goto resolution table from these labelled positions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_label_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node
    Let hir_node be proc hir_create_continue from HIR
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_node, "lua_label", ast_node.value
    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The goto translator is the dual of translate_label_statement: it produces a
continue node tagged with "lua_goto" metadata holding the target label name.
The two together let the semantic analyser pair each goto with its label by
metadata lookup.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_goto_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast_node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node
    Let hir_node be proc hir_create_continue from HIR
    proc hir_set_metadata from HIR with hir_node, "lua_goto", ast_node.value
    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A Lua block is a sequence of statements that share lexical scope. We translate
each child statement in source order and append to a HIR block. We do NOT
establish a new scope here - scope creation is the semantic analyser's job
because not every Lua block introduces a new scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_block" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, block_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let stmt_count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with block_node

    Let hir_block be proc hir_create_block from HIR

    Let stmt_index be 0
    While stmt_index is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with block_node, stmt_index
        Let stmt_hir be proc translate_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_ast
        proc hir_add_statement from HIR with hir_block, stmt_hir
        Set stmt_index to stmt_index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_block
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The program entry treats the top-level block as the module body, which mirrors
Lua's semantics: a Lua file is essentially the body of an anonymous function.
We translate that block once and add each of its statements as a top-level
declaration on the HIR module so downstream module-level consumers (which
iterate hir_get_declarations) see the file's statements directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_program" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaToHIRContext be ctx_ptr

    Let program_ast be ctx.ast_root
    Let block_ast be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with program_ast, 0
    Let block_hir be proc translate_block with ctx_ptr, block_ast

    proc hir_add_declaration from HIR with ctx.hir_module, block_hir

    Return ctx.hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry point - builds a fresh translation context from the AST root and
invokes translate_program. The context is not returned because the caller does
not need the diagnostic list at this layer; callers needing fine-grained error
reporting construct the context manually via create_translation_context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_lua_to_hir" takes ast_root as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be proc create_translation_context with ast_root
    Let hir_module be proc translate_program with ctx
    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Quick predicate that consults the had_error flag set by translation_error
during the recursive walk. Returns the raw integer flag rather than computing
list length because the flag costs an int-load while list length costs an
indirection plus traversal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "had_translation_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaToHIRContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.had_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the underlying List handle holding the error message strings. The list
is owned by the context, so callers must not destroy or mutate it - they read
the entries, format them for display, then destroy the context as a whole.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_translation_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaToHIRContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.errors
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's LANG_LUA arm.
Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: create_lexer builds the lexer state,
tokenize returns the token list, create_parser wraps the tokens, parse_program
walks them into a Lua AST root, and translate_lua_to_hir lowers the AST into
HIR.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
On a parse failure (ast_root == 0) the wrapper short-circuits to 0 so
downstream stages do not see a half-formed module.
@End Implementation
Process called "lua_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source_code
    Let tokens be proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with tokens
    Let ast_root be proc parse_program from Parser with parser
    If ast_root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc translate_lua_to_hir with ast_root
End Process
